comment_text:
@TheDiaryOfACEO

I have narcolepsy. I have, for my entire adult life, had a dysfunctional brain. The best way to describe having narcolepsy is that parts of your brain go to sleep when you don't want them to (during the day) and parts wake up when you don't want them to (during the night) and you functionally feel chronically severely sleep deprived. Your sleep cycles are disrupted and out of order, and your ability to stay awake and have normal cognitive functioning and retain memories, for example, is greatly affected. It's one of those diseases that completely disrupts and in my case ruins your life. I've been completely unable to get it under any real control more than a couple of years at a time, usually by being on high doses of stimulants, which causes its own set of problems. I have ADHD. Severely, because these symptoms overlap some daytime symptoms of narcolepsy. I am 41 and I feel like my brain is 200. I would love to know if Dr amen has any knowledge or information on what someone like me is supposed to do to have some semblance of a normal life. The worst part is, now, I have 2 young children who are being modeled a completely dysfunctional way of living because I'm physically incapable of modeling anything better. Their dad does the best he can to help out and to make up for the dysfunctional modeling they get from me, but I'm their mother. I really need help with this. Even sleep specialists of whom I've seen several over the years, just don't have any real answers for me. I've done CBT, taken several types and combinations of drugs, and made every effort I can to combat this. But, no pun intended, I'm just SO TIRED of living like this. There has to be something more.

comment_text:
I love this interview! I wish you could ask whether they've ever scanned the brains of truly devoted men of God—like pastors or others who live with deep faith—and compared those scans to people who don't walk closely with God. It would be fascinating to see how the brain responds when someone truly has God at the center of their life. After all, God says, 'I have not given you a spirit of fear, but of power, love, and a sound mind.' Fear, worry, and anxiety are not from God; He promises peace because He provides.

All worldly things separate us from God—they create a foothold for Satan to introduce demonic spirits such as addiction, drunkenness, lust, perversion, depression, and more. But when you have God within you, you gain the spiritual discernment and authority to rebuke those spirits in the name of Jesus. You can plead the blood of Jesus over your thoughts, your life, your body, and declare healing and restoration.

Start praying to Jesus to reveal everything to you—that alone can be one of the most powerful first steps toward healing your brain and renewing your mind. God has already given us all the answers; they're in the Bible. Science is simply uncovering the fine details of how God designed it all—like a behind-the-scenes look at His creation.

God has even shown us how to eat and live healthy in the Bible. So whether it's mental, spiritual, or physical well-being, God has already laid it out. We just need to seek Him, listen, and apply His wisdom.

About 1:30  RE tantrums:  my daughter was prekindergarten when she threw a rare tantrum in the grocery store. I warned her that was not an appropriate behavior and she was unnecessarily bothering others and if you  didn’t stop (“we can talk about what’s bothering you later.”) we will have to leave the store. The tantrum didn’t stop. Without arguing, I took her and the cart to the front of the store; told a clerk sorry, but I have to leave. And I did. We never had  an  in store tantrum again. This took planning and a few deep breaths 🤣
Another in store plan that helped: “you may choose one item not on our shopping list. If you change your mind  the first item has to go back in its place. This stopped all the “may we get this… ?” arguments.

The biggest parenting mistake I think people make is over parenting. People seek fixes when they're constantly thrust into these neurotic environments that incentive inaction at a young age. Dopamine is the chemical responsible for movement which for all intents and purposes is the act of overcoming inaction as far as stimulus -> response relationships are concerned.

Focus more on teaching what habits to do rather than what not do and you lower the reward threshold so people derive pleasure from doing normal people things. While it's just a hunch this would explain why the more we know about the brain the worse we seem to get at raising kids with heathy minds.

video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text:
Thinking you might have ADHD? Ask yourself these:

Do I often start tasks but struggle to finish them?

Is my mind constantly jumping from one thought to the next?

Do I find it hard to sit still or relax, even when I want to?

Do I frequently lose things like keys, phones, or focus?

Do I interrupt others or blurt things out without thinking?

Do I forget appointments, deadlines, or important details?

Do I hyper-focus on things I enjoy but struggle with boring tasks?

Do I feel restless, impatient, or like I’m driven by a motor?

Do I struggle with time management and procrastination?

Do I get easily distracted, even by small things?

Did I show signs of these behaviors as a child?

If you relate to a lot of these, especially across different areas of life (work, relationships, daily tasks), it’s worth chatting to a professional. ADHD looks different in everyone—but awareness is a powerful first step.

comment_text: Residing in Poland as an African expat and English teacher hasn't been a walk in the park. (The beauty does exist, of course, like everywhere else.) I am constantly reminded how their history broke every generation, in every school project, or roleplay,  - the constant negativity or pessimism or complaining from the majority of the students, parents, and the environment somewhat wore me down;  I even fell into depression 2 years ago. As a 29-year-old African: "What is depression and where does it come from? This is new."  It could've been the climate, could've been the culture, definitely abusing alcohol. I didn't know how to help my brain. I turned to smoking and drinking just to cope or escape my reality, until ear surgery forced me to recover without these things, and been good without it.  Now, I see it even more clearly — negativity here is normalised. Abuse of alcohol is normalised. Spoiling your child is normalised. It’s made me miss Africa deeply. We might not have much, but we do know discipline - kinda don't have a choice in that regard, or you have your grandmother or parent throwing or hitting you with a shoe. Despite our home struggles, crime, or poverty, there’s always joy, community, and emotional warmth. As a modern teacher dealing with kids/teens behaving like zoo animals, or non-empathetic adults and parents, I'm not sure what my brain goes through 5 days a week.  I wish I could afford a brain scan with Dr Daniel Amen. Great video - Learned a ton. Saffron it is.

ANTs 
1.What is the thought? Write it down. What type is it: all or nothing, less than, guilt, mind reading, fortune telling, blaming?
2. Is it true? Is it absolutely true?
3. How does that thought makes me feel, act and what is the outcome of believing that thought.

5. What is the opposite thought? Is that true?

7. Meditate on the opposite of the thought that is bothering you.

comment_text:
Very enjoyable discussion. I don't usually watch these all the way through, but this one and the CTE one are exceptional. 

My ACE score is an 8 or 9 depending on if family going to jail counts as a yes for the household members going to prison question. My mother would read me news articles about kids tortured and killed by their parents to convince me that I was not being abused and should be grateful... I'm certain I have Borderline Personality Disorder, I'm hyper vigilant, and flit in and out of other mental illnesses depending on the stress levels in my life.

But, I refuse to take prescription meds for the same reason he listed (they mask rather than fix), and therapy was not useful. Instead I read studies and try natural remedies. As Legally Blonde says, fit people don't kill people (usually). 

I learned to love the gym and the endorphine rush, spend more time in the sun even in winter to help with S.A.D. and autoimmune issues, try to avoid high levels of sugar since they increase depression and feeling sickly, avoid caffeine because it often sets off manic episodes that can last days or up to 2 weeks. In addition, supplements like bacopa, ashwaganda, rhodiola (to replace caffeine), HUM PMS Supplement, Olly Stress supplement (my favorite), and an annual mushroom trip to reset me all do their part when necessary. As for my BPD, I use redirection into less harmful behaviors as much as possible and try to watch the company I keep. Being around the wrong people can make you or break you with this disorder. 

Lifestyle changes could cure most mental illnesses. Cultural changes could as well.

Questions to ask/ write down about your negative thoughts:
1. Is it true?
2. Is it absolutely true?
3. How do I feel, act, and what's the outcome of having this thought?

5. Take the thought and turn it to the opposite and ask yourself, is that true?
+How many of these things can't I handle
Then meditate on the opposite of the thought ... (take these thoughts captive)
~people who are depressed are infested with negative, but you can train yourself towards positivity
Also consider that happiness is a moral obligation (it affects your world)

comment_text:
It would be brilliant to see Gabor Mate and Caroline Leaf sit around a table and join in this conversation, particularly on subject of anxiety, depression, ADD, bipolar and schizophrenia, especially in children.  It would also good for Gabor to share his findings on the use of psychedelics to help heal trauma. 
I really enjoy listening to Dr.Amen and have learnt so much from him, 2 things he mentioned though that I’d like to share. 
Firstly the comments on the Keto diet doesn’t have enough vegetables to give your gut enough diversity in your microbiome…I started the Zoe app in Jan 2024 (after watching a podcast on here at the end of 2023).  Before that I had always eaten a high fat, high protein, low carb foods.  The zoe test confirmed my body didn’t react well to sugar and my variety of microbiome was poor.  I followed the Zoe app for 4 months very strictly I can honestly say this absolutely wrecked my health!! I had serious IBS, I had to stop training as my stool was that lose.  It got to a point where I could hardly travel anywhere as I needed the toilet.  This caused bleeding from inside my anus and intestines.  I had to have a camera up my backside and large polyps removed which were there from my non stops toilet action.  
(TBH alarm bells rang when the Zoe app was  recommending red wine as a health drink and promoting up to 5 cups of caffeinated coffee a day!!!)
I scraped the Zoe app after 4 months ( I paid for a year) as I had brain fog, confusion, fatigue, low mood and anxiety.  
I switched to eating nothing but meat and within 2 weeks nearly all my symptoms went, bar the headaches…..
The 2nd thing…I am slightly darked skinned and live in the north of the UK where we only get about 7 weeks of sunshine a year.  Nearly all experts recommend vitamin D, so I had been taking one for over a year.
I sent off a hair sample to have my heavy metals and elements evaluated…. I was instantly told to stop any Vitamin D supplements I was taking.  It turned out I was overdosing on Vitamin D….they found this as I was over producing Calcium in my body (due to the high levels of Vitamin D)…further more my Potassium levels where at zero (with over sauna use)….this combination (calcium and potassium) can give your Thyroid levels at a cellular level (might not show up in a blood test) and mine where off the scale showing I had a seriously under active thyroid, which I have now re-balanced and my headaches have completely gone.  
I’d recommend knowing your levels like Dr Amen says before you supplement anything and remember we are all individuals, what works for someone might not work for you….for me improving the variety of my microbiome made me ill and following the Zoe damaged my health

video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text:
I may be late. But the conversation around cannabis use is always an interesting one. I wouldn't say that any use of it is innocuous, however, I do call into question the validity of how controlled the research is. Cannabis development has come a long way since the 60s. There's always this blanket generalisation of its harmful effects. Yet, we rarely get any specifications beyond someone being a heavy smoker. What does that mean? We also know that a lot of funding was put into the demonizing of cannabis and a lot of researchers lead with that notion in mind.

In any research involving, lets say chemistry or physics, all variables must be considered, less they throw the entire research out. We need clear specifications. How long have these people smoked? Do they smoke with tobacco? Do they do any other drugs? What strain of cannabis have they been smoking? Has this been cross-examined with participants who've never smoked, and are willing to smoke under strict conditions and specifications? Did any of the smokers suffer from memory loss, anxiety or depression prior to taking cannabis? And so on.

I could be an exception. For example, I suffered from depression and anxiety before I ever smoked. I also have issues sleeping. Due to high levels of stress, I also suffer from poor memory, mainly relating to my past--rather than present. When I started smoking in the UK, we have what's called Skunk(usually superficially potent cannabis/high levels of THC). Most can say Skunk is objectively bad. Most who smoke it heavily and with tobacco for years tend to have paranoia, panic attacks, bouts of psychosis, and in some cases withdrawals, you name it. However, since the advent and introduction to the US market, most smokers moved onto lighter strains that have alleviated stress, anxiety, and soothed insomnia with little to no side-effects. And I can attest to those results myself(but "trust me bro," isn't enough, I know). Despite that fact, I never suffered any of the aforementioned side effects besides brain fog when smoking Skunk specifically. I also face no withdrawals or strong desires to smoke if I haven't smoked in while. Instead, I get a pleasant "it would be nice," at best.

Thank you for attending my TedTalks. And I release my opinion into the void.

comment_text:
How does the book explain the evolution of healthcare policies over time

In *"The Hidden War on Healthcare,"* Alex Pierce explains the evolution of healthcare policies by highlighting key historical trends and their impact on today's system:

1. **Post-War Expansion**: The book discusses how World War II led to advancements like mass production of penicillin and increased hospital construction, shaping early healthcare access and infrastructure[2].

2. **Employer-Based Insurance**: During the mid-20th century, health benefits became tied to employment, creating a fragmented system reliant on private insurance rather than universal coverage[2].

3. **Failed Universal Healthcare Efforts**: Pierce examines attempts like President Clinton’s 1990s proposal for universal healthcare, which failed due to political opposition and lobbying by private insurers[2].

4. **Technological and Pharmaceutical Growth**: The rise of expensive medical technologies and direct-to-consumer pharmaceutical advertising in the late 20th century contributed to escalating healthcare costs[2][7].

5. **COVID-19 Pandemic**: Recent policies during the pandemic exposed systemic weaknesses, including the prioritization of profits over equitable care[7].

These historical developments are framed as contributing to a profit-driven system that often neglects preventive care and affordability.

Citations:
[1] [PDF] Lessons from the history of British health policy https://researchonline.lshtm.ac.uk/id/eprint/4671562/1/Mold_etal_2023_Lessons_from_the_History_of_British_Health_Policy.pdf

comment_text:
How Food Additives Are Contributing to Brain Damage
Most modern processed foods contain chemical additives, preservatives, artificial sweeteners, and emulsifiers that are wreaking havoc on the brain. Here’s how:

1. Neurotoxic Food Additives That Are Shrinking the Brain
Aspartame (Artificial Sweetener - Found in Diet Sodas, Sugar-Free Products)

Breaks down into methanol and formaldehyde, both of which are neurotoxins.
Linked to brain fog, headaches, memory loss, mood swings, and depression.
Studies show it damages neurons and could contribute to Alzheimer’s and Parkinson’s disease.
Monosodium Glutamate (MSG - Found in Fast Food, Chips, Seasonings, Packaged Snacks, Chinese Food, Canned Soups, and Processed Meats)

Excitotoxin that overstimulates brain cells until they die, leading to learning disabilities and neurodegeneration.
Linked to migraines, seizures, and ADHD-like symptoms.
Increases dopamine cravings, making junk food more addictive.
Artificial Food Dyes (Red 40, Yellow 5, Blue 1 - Found in Candy, Cereals, Sodas, Snacks, Processed Foods)

Linked to hyperactivity, attention deficits, and aggressive behavior (especially in children).
Can trigger inflammation in the brain, leading to mood disorders, anxiety, and cognitive decline.
Some dyes like Red 40 and Yellow 5 contain benzidine, a carcinogenic (cancer-causing) compound.
2. Preservatives That Are Poisoning the Brain
Sodium Benzoate (Found in Sodas, Fruit Juices, Pickles, Processed Foods)

When mixed with vitamin C (common in juices), it forms benzene, a known neurotoxin and carcinogen.
Linked to neuroinflammation, anxiety, and depression.
Alters dopamine and serotonin levels, worsening mental health conditions.
BHT & BHA (Found in Cereal, Gum, Butter, Snack Foods, Processed Meats, and Packaged Foods)

Classified as “possibly carcinogenic” by the WHO.
Interferes with hormones and brain neurotransmitters.
Linked to hyperactivity, ADHD, and cognitive dysfunction.
3. Emulsifiers That Are Destroying Gut-Brain Health
Polysorbate 80 & Carrageenan (Found in Ice Cream, Salad Dressings, Non-Dairy Milk, Processed Foods)
Damages the gut lining, leading to leaky gut syndrome, which allows toxins to reach the brain.
Increases inflammation, which accelerates Alzheimer’s and depression.
Alters the gut microbiome, negatively affecting mood and cognition.

1:42:36 surely this is textbook Hyperfocus!? It's really common for ADHDers to have the ability to focus intensely on something specific for insane periods of time. Often losing the desire to do anything else like eat or switch task (spoiler alert - this is not normal or healthy). The trouble is it's not something we have voluntary control over. Like Dr Amen said, when it's novel, exciting and under time pressure ADHDers have no issue with focus. 

'Attention Deficit' is poor wording for the disorder - Attention Dysregulation' is more appropriate. People with untreated ADHD struggle to every find a healthy balance to their life - swinging from intense periods of hyperfocus (very draining), to weeks of inability to focus on necessary life tasks.

video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text:
With all due respect, BUT….
1. “Psilocybin Makes Your Brain Look Older” 
	•	Dr. Amen bases this on SPECT scans, a type of brain imaging he often uses to evaluate blood flow in the brain.
	•	He claims that psychedelic use can lead to reduced blood flow in certain brain regions, making the brain appear “older” on scans.

Why this is misleading:
	•	Most neuroscience research suggests the opposite—that psilocybin enhances neuroplasticity, strengthens neural connections, and may protect against age-related decline.
	•	A 2020 study published in Cell Reports found that psychedelics promote dendritic growth and synaptogenesis, meaning they strengthen brain cells rather than age them.
	•	Psilocybin has been studied for Alzheimer’s and cognitive resilience, with evidence suggesting it might help protect against neurodegeneration.
author: @yuraro6098

video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text:
2. “Psilocybin is Addictive”
	•	Completely false from a pharmacological standpoint.
	•	Unlike alcohol, nicotine, or opioids, psilocybin does not create physical dependency or compulsive use.
	•	In fact, it’s being researched as a treatment for addiction (alcohol, smoking, and opioids).
	•	You quickly develop tolerance, making frequent use ineffective.
author: @yuraro6098

video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text:
And so…
•    Current neuroscience supports psilocybin’s role in brain health, neuroplasticity, and emotional well-being.
	•	It is not addictive, and evidence suggests it may protect brain function rather than harm it over time.
	•	Dr. Amen’s concerns about “brain aging” are not widely supported by other experts or clinical studies.

video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text:
**Key Insights from "The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!"**

This discussion with Dr. Daniel Amen, a renowned psychiatrist and brain health expert, delves into the critical factors influencing brain health across the lifespan, from childhood development to aging and Alzheimer's prevention. Here are the key insights:

**1. Brain Health is Paramount:**

*   The brain is the organ of intelligence, character, and decision-making. Its proper function is essential for a fulfilling life. \[[02:59]]
*   Many people are unaware of the link between brain function and issues like poor decisions, anxiety, and relationship problems. \[[03:15]]
*   "Brain rot" is a growing concern, reflecting anxieties about habits like social media and pornography shrinking the brain. \[[04:43, 05:04]]
*   Prioritizing brain health is not just about preventing disease; it's about optimizing the mind's ability to achieve happiness. \[[03:35]]

**2. The Developing Brain is Vulnerable:**

*   Exposure to pornography is extremely hazardous for developing brains, especially in young boys. \[06:06]
*   Excessive dopamine stimulation from pornography, gaming, gambling, and substance abuse can desensitize the brain's reward system. \[[06:41, 07:36]]
*   The prefrontal cortex, responsible for decision-making, isn't fully developed until age 25, making supervision crucial for teenagers. \[[08:08, 08:17]]
*   A key parenting mistake is giving in to tantrums, which teaches children that manipulative behavior is effective. \[[01:31:00]]

**3. Alcohol and Drugs are Detrimental:**

*   Even moderate alcohol consumption is detrimental to the brain and increases the risk of several cancers. \[[11:11, 11:25]]
*   Alcohol disrupts white matter in the brain, impairs decision-making, and can lead to premature brain aging. \[[13:29, 14:16, 14:59]]
*   Heavy drinking causes the brain to shrink and become less active, impacting cognitive function and overall health. \[[15:50, 16:22, 16:41]]
*   Marijuana use is linked to decreased brain activity, smaller hippocampus volume, and increased risk of anxiety, depression, and suicide in teenagers. \[[22:41, 23:02]]

**4. Trauma and Negative Thinking Impact Brain Health:**

*   Early childhood trauma can be visible on brain scans and increases the risk of various health problems and a shorter life expectancy. \[[39:28, 41:05]]
*   Negative thinking decreases activity in the prefrontal cortex, impacting motivation, focus, and mood. \[[01:01, 45:35]]
*   Practicing positivity-biased training and managing automatic negative thoughts (ANTS) can improve brain function and mental well-being. \[[36:16, 45:35]]

**5. Brain Reserve and Protective Factors:**

*   "Brain reserve" refers to the brain's resilience and ability to cope with trauma or aging. \[[01:05:20]]
*   Brain reserve starts before conception and is influenced by genetics, maternal health during pregnancy, nutrition, and experiences. \[[01:05:43, 01:06:12]]
*   Factors that build brain reserve include a healthy diet, exercise, avoiding smoking and excessive alcohol, and engaging in mentally stimulating activities. \[[01:08:40]]
*   Conscientiousness and good frontal lobe function are linked to a longer life. \[[47:16]]

**6. Alzheimer's Prevention:**

*   Alzheimer's is a complex disease with multiple risk factors, including genetics, head trauma, toxins, mental health, infections, and diabesity (high blood sugar and/or being overweight). \[[01:09:34, 01:09:51]]
*   A carbohydrate-based diet significantly increases the risk of Alzheimer's, while a diet rich in healthy fats and protein reduces the risk. \[[01:14:39, 01:14:10, 01:14:29]]
*   Maintaining healthy blood sugar levels is crucial for brain health and Alzheimer's prevention. \[[01:13:26]]

**7. The Importance of Purpose and Spirituality:**

*   Living with purpose is essential for brain health and overall well-being. \[[02:03:24]]
*   Purpose can be linked to making the world a better place. \[[02:02:53]]
*   Religious belief and prayer can have positive effects on brain structure and function, similar to meditation. \[[02:04:17, 02:07:00]]

**8. AI and Technology: A Double-Edged Sword:**

*   AI has the potential to both help and hinder brain development. \[[01:58:43, 01:59:21]]
*   In the short run, AI may reduce brain activity, which is detrimental. \[[01:58:56]]
*   Artificial social connections may not provide the same benefits as real social connections. \[[02:01:21]]

**Conclusion:**

This conversation emphasizes the profound impact of lifestyle choices, environmental factors, and even early childhood experiences on brain health. Dr. Amen advocates for a proactive approach, urging individuals to prioritize brain-healthy habits, protect developing brains from harm, and cultivate a sense of purpose and connection. So interesting. I love this podcast, particularly the episodes related to health. One thing I’ve noticed is that correlation is sometimes presented as causation—like when discussing the link between obesity and dementia. While there is clearly a correlation, both may stem from the same underlying root cause, such as a loss of microbiome diversity (which research supports for both). And because of that, the habits that benefit brain health and weight management may be the same—since they support a healthy microbiome.

A common issue with medicin is that they are only looking at the extremes. such collection of data is not scientifically sound. Its useful information, but I doubt that the image that evolves is the truth, its at best an oversimplified model of the human race. The indians use 4 base types in their model, a step forward. But western medicine based just on statistics is very questionable from a scientific perspective. When I helped my girlfriend with her PhD thesis 30 years ago, I realized that medicine is not science like physics. 
The statistic is bad, the modeling is bad, etc. It is still mostly try and error in a badly understood system - the human body. Its getting better, but  way to go!

video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text:
As someone studying and researching in the neurology field and dealing with people with dementia, I appreciate this comprehensive discussion on brain health and lifestyle factors. It provides valuable insights into mitigating the risk of neurodegenerative diseases like Alzheimer’s.
This is not medical advice. 
The emphasis on modifiable risk factors—such as diet, physical activity, and mental engagement—is particularly compelling. Recent studies have highlighted that a combination of healthy lifestyle traits may substantially reduce the risk of Alzheimer's disease.
Additionally, research indicates that addressing factors like physical inactivity, uncontrolled diabetes, high blood pressure, and hearing loss can further diminish dementia risk.

This underscores the importance of a holistic approach to brain health, integrating both preventive measures and proactive lifestyle modifications. It’s also noteworthy that personalized health and lifestyle changes, such as increased exercise and socialization, can delay or even prevent memory loss in higher-risk older adults.

One aspect that deserves particular attention is the deleterious effect of alcohol on the brain. Studies consistently show that alcohol accelerates brain atrophy, damages white matter integrity, and increases the risk of both Alzheimer’s and vascular dementia. Even moderate alcohol consumption has been linked to reduced cognitive function over time, contradicting earlier beliefs that small amounts may be protective. Chronic alcohol use, in particular, compromises the prefrontal cortex, leading to impaired decision-making, reduced impulse control, and heightened vulnerability to cognitive decline.

Moreover, cardiovascular health plays a critical role in brain health. Hypertension, diabetes, obesity, and dyslipidemia are well-established risk factors not only for vascular dementia but also for Alzheimer’s disease. Poor cerebral perfusion and chronic inflammation from these conditions exacerbate neurodegeneration, making cardiovascular risk factor management a crucial component of dementia prevention. The link between heart and brain health is undeniable: what’s good for the heart is good for the brain.

Another underrated yet essential factor in cognitive longevity is sleep quality. Despite mounting evidence on its role in brain detoxification, synaptic plasticity, and memory consolidation, sleep remains underappreciated in mainstream discussions on dementia prevention. Chronic sleep deprivation and poor sleep hygiene have been linked to an increased accumulation of beta-amyloid and tau proteins, both hallmarks of Alzheimer’s disease. Sleep disturbances also exacerbate metabolic and cardiovascular risk factors, further compounding cognitive decline. Prioritizing consistent, high-quality sleep should be seen as a cornerstone of brain health, on par with diet and exercise.
An often overlooked yet powerful protective factor against cognitive decline is cognitive reserve—the brain’s ability to adapt and compensate for damage by utilizing alternative neural pathways. Lifelong learning, engaging in intellectually stimulating activities, and constantly challenging the brain with new skills (such as learning a language, playing an instrument, or solving complex problems) have been shown to build and strengthen this reserve. Research suggests that individuals with higher cognitive reserve exhibit slower cognitive decline and lower dementia risk, even when brain pathology is present.

This discussion reinforces the urgent need for public awareness and early intervention, emphasizing that dementia is not an inevitable consequence of aging, but rather the result of decades of lifestyle and health choices. A proactive, multifaceted strategy that includes nutritional optimization, regular physical exercise, cognitive stimulation, cardiovascular risk management, sleep optimization and complete avoidance of neurotoxic substances like alcohol can significantly protect long-term brain function.

comment_text:
I've been smoking for coming up to 12 years now and I'm trying to quit, and I'm finding it difficult to find a replacement. Because I don't want to replace it with alcohol or cigarettes or anything just as bad for me. And I'm struggling to just sit there and deal with it. I don't smoke through the day when I'm working, I try and hold off as long as I can. Sometimes that's 5:30 when I finish work, other times it's 8pm after I've had dinner. But it's my wind down and chill out in the evening. And this is also a habit I have learnt from my parents - but theirs is alcohol. They finished work and would go to the pub. So I just learnt that habit but don't like being drunk. 

If I can't find a healthy habit to replace it with and just need to deal with all the emotions and thoughts that come with it, I still need to function in society. I don't want to be angry and biting at people. And so, that's something that stops me quitting because I don't want to accidentally be a bitch to those around me. 

Also, there is a part of me that doesn't want to quit. That does enjoy it. I just don't want to spend the money on it any more. I also want to live my life and be happier. To travel more. To do more activities and events. I  want more energy to spend time with my friends children, and maybe one day for my own children. 

But by the God's, is it difficult...

video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text:
🐘 The Elephant in the Room: EMFs. This was by far the biggest failure of the episode. With all his talk about brain health and what harms the brain, not once does he mention electromagnetic frequencies (EMFs)—a proven and growing concern (or DAOC never asked about it either). Governments and corporations are actively increasing our exposure through 5G (upcoming 6G), Starlink, WiFi, Bluetooth, and wireless devices, yet this major environmental factor was completely ignored. (Not to mention ignorance around the subject… what a disappointment).

We are being constantly bombarded with radiation that is reshaping brain function, and instead of addressing this, he keeps repeating “don’t put crap in your brain”—referring only to diet, alcohol, and substances. That’s a huge oversight (also from DAOC that did not ask this). Brain health is not just about what we eat or drink; it’s about the environments we live in, the air we breathe, and the radiation we're exposed to daily. Why wasn’t this addressed? Is it inconvenient? Too controversial? Or is it just outside his narrow research bubble?. I really want to learn more. 

I got some valuable takeaways, but his perspective on certain topics felt outdated and super biased. He clearly has access to an immense amount of brain scan data, but his approach is narrow, dismissive, and often comes across as lacking real curiosity beyond his own established theories. 

When he talks about ADHD, it sounds like a push to medicate everyone, and his own comments about his daughter were unsettling. If straight As require medication, maybe the system itself is the issue, not the child.

And let’s talk about his absolute dismissal of psilocybin. The science is there; major institutions like Johns Hopkins and Imperial College London are conducting serious studies on its benefits, yet he waves it off as just another 1960s street drug. If you're going to criticize something, at least acknowledge the research. All along the podcast, he's full of projections.

And him repeatedly name-dropping Justin Bieber, Miley Cyrus, and the Kardashians as if their involvement adds credibility. Honestly, the more he mentioned them, the less I cared.

Final Verdict: 4/10 – Interesting but full of blind spots. (This is just personal; I just did not vibe with him. There's something that doesn't make him super trustworthy…)

This was one of the weakest episodes I’ve seen. Dr. Amen has some insights, but his dismissive attitude, bias against certain topics, and refusal to engage with emerging science made this frustrating to watch. He leans too heavily on his massive dataset of brain scans without acknowledging the broader picture of human experience.

Ps1: Watch in 1.25 or 1.5 speed. I promise you, you will not notice the difference.
Ps: Cool intro with the coins. Go team!

video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text:
Claims That Need More Evidence or Are Misleading ⚠
Saffron as an Antidepressant

Some studies suggest saffron may be as effective as SSRIs for mild depression, but more large-scale trials are needed.
Unlike SSRIs, saffron isn’t regulated for dosage or purity.
Brain Shrinkage from Alcohol & Marijuana

Long-term heavy alcohol use definitely shrinks the brain, but moderate drinking's effects are still debated.
Marijuana use affects cognitive function, but brain shrinkage claims are not fully proven.
The Idea That Depression Has Many Causes (Like Chest Pain)

While depression has multiple causes, it is not as simple as comparing it to chest pain.
Brain scans are not a diagnostic tool for depression in current clinical practice.
Claim That Most People Can Recover Brain Health in Months

While lifestyle changes help brain function, some damage (e.g., from chronic alcoholism or repeated head injuries) may be permanent.
Unverified or Oversimplified Claims ❌
COVID & Alzheimer's

Some studies suggest COVID may increase Alzheimer’s risk, but long-term data is lacking.
“Brain Rot” and Social Media

While excessive social media can affect attention and mood, the idea that it shrinks the brain is an exaggeration.
Psilocybin (Magic Mushrooms) Leading to Psychosis in 300% More Cases

Psilocybin therapy shows promise for depression, but claims of a 300% increase in psychosis lack strong evidence.
Conclusion: Mostly True, But Some Exaggerations
Dr. Amen’s overall message is valid: Protect your brain with a good diet, exercise, sleep, and cognitive health.
However, some claims lack scientific consensus, are overstated, or need more research.
His use of brain scans for psychiatric conditions is controversial, as most psychiatrists do not use them for depression or ADHD diagnosis.

But not really. @22:42 I didn’t look up the study he published himself but I did check the other one he refers to. The study found a “SMALL TO MEDIUM EFFECT SIZE”. 

That statistical term (small to medium effect size) indicates that the observed differences in brain activation were noticeable but not large.

The study examined brain activation over 7 tasks. Out of 7 tasks, only 1 showed anything noticeable, “a small to medium effect size”. 

Heavy lifetime users were more likely to be male, to have lower income, and to have lower levels of education than nonusers. Heavy lifetime users also had higher scores for nicotine dependence severity and alcohol use relative to those with negative THC test results.

Even with all of that, there was no noticeable difference in 6 tasks, and only a small to medium noticeable difference in 1 task.

comment_text:
> My two and half year old son stated to have a fit in the middle of the grocery store because he was not getting what he wanted. I started crying and screaming just like him, he never did that again.

This is child abuse, very similar to simply leaving a child to cry, or hitting a child to make them shut up. Just because the child goes silent does not mean the problem is solved. All you teach a child with that particular example is that if they don't stop displaying emotions immediately, you, their essential caretaker, will have a meltdown. They learn their emotions are life-threatening to display. You aren't teaching them anything, you are simply threatening them in more indirect ways.

You are teaching the child that they must manage your emotions somehow despite their complete lack of any emotional management skills themselves. Doing this to your child creates psychological trauma. it does not soothe the child or teach them how to manage their emotions, it is a simple transfer of responsibility entirely onto the child. Typically what happens is the child, seeing their essential caretaker becoming unstable and dangerous, perceives this as a threat to their life. Their brain enters fight or flight mode and shuts up. You teach them to dissociate, which makes it even more difficult for them to learn proper emotional management as they have little access to what they are actually feeling. This kind of behaviour, repeated, literally causes PTSD, in particular, CPTSD.

Expecting a two and a half year old to calm themselves down is unreasonable.

In that particular example, you took the easy road for yourself. I cannot recommend that approach over the long term because it trades instantaneous convenience for long term complications. It is worth noting that in the worst cases, people will appear functional externally for many years, before finally burning out on unresolved emotional issues. If you teach a child to hide their emotions, you will have no idea what the internal health of that person actually is.

comment_text:
@22:42 I didn’t look up the study he published himself but I did check the other one he refers to. The study found a “SMALL TO MEDIUM EFFECT SIZE”. 

That statistical term (small to medium effect size) indicates that the observed differences in brain activation were noticeable but not large.

The study examined brain activation over 7 tasks. Out of 7 tasks, only 1 showed anything noticeable, “a small to medium effect size”. 

Heavy lifetime users were more likely to be male, to have lower income, and to have lower levels of education than nonusers. Heavy lifetime users also had higher scores for nicotine dependence severity and alcohol use relative to those with negative THC test results.

Even with all of that, there was no noticeable difference in 6 tasks, and only a small to medium noticeable difference in 1 task. 

Yet with all of the lower education, and nicotine use, and alcohol use, he wants to claim this study irrefutably shows that “marijuana is bad”. 

Btw, it was 1,003 participants. Not “1,021… 1,027” that he quotes. Clearly, his memory ain’t so great. Wonder what he’s been smokin’

Based on this weak study, I’m not wasting anymore time looking up the study he published. Have a feeling it’s just more Reefer Madness bologna 🤦‍♂️

@REBEL_k22  1. Cut off all the people who can get you weed. I mean literally. If you want to stop, you won't feel bad about it.
2. Change your routine. Every detail of every hour. It's not about doing more, but stick to few things and getting better. Work, business, hobbies, fitness all you can think not to be alone and bored.

@22:42 I didn’t look up the study he published himself but I did check the other one he refers to. The study found a “SMALL TO MEDIUM EFFECT SIZE”. 

That statistical term (small to medium effect size) indicates that the observed differences in brain activation were noticeable but not large.

The study examined brain activation over 7 tasks. Out of 7 tasks, only 1 showed anything noticeable, “a small to medium effect size”. 

Heavy lifetime users were more likely to be male, to have lower income, and to have lower levels of education than nonusers. Heavy lifetime users also had higher scores for nicotine dependence severity and alcohol use relative to those with negative THC test results.

Even with all of that, there was no noticeable difference in 6 tasks, and only a small to medium noticeable difference in 1 task. 

Yet with all of the lower education, and nicotine use, and alcohol use, he wants to claim this study irrefutably shows that “marijuana is bad”. 

Btw, it was 1,003 participants. Not “1,021… 1,027” that he quotes. Clearly, his memory ain’t so great. Wonder what he’s been smokin’

video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text: @ I have always felt that the general conversation around intelligence between species was quite unfair and silly. Like you mentioned, a fish might not know how to climb a tree because they simply don’t need that for survival, don’t possess the physical structures to do so (no fault of their own), and who’s to say that had the fish been given the the physical means to climb trees that they couldn’t learn to do so! (If we’d wanna base intelligence in that way). But in a broader discussion, there’s no consensus regarding how to even define or measure intelligence and or how to accurately place an individual or creature upon what would undoubtedly be a spectrum of intelligence. That being said, it often becomes a silly conversation of less meaningful opinions that just stops feeling scientific and beneficial to the greater understanding, imo. But measuring something like to degradation of cognitive function within someone over a period of time of heavy drinking, I think it’s fair to draw some conclusions about how the brains may have declined as a result, and assign what has diminished as “intelligence”… although I think many, including myself, would trade to word intelligence for cognitive function when speaking more professionally about it. I think cognitive function is much different than intelligence, but I think there can be passes to use the words interchangeably in a more casual discussion. And also, I believe that cognitive function could very well be one of the more prevalent metrics to define the health and performance framework of the brain. 🧠

comment_text:
Actually, I wish Dr. Amen spoke more about video games with kids, but he only briefly touched on it at the end. I grew up on video games. But categorizing all games in one basket of "video games" seems inaccurate. 

For instance, I grew up on JRPG games (final fantasy) or platforming games (Mario/sonic) that required hand-eye coordination, featured stories, problem solving, and characters with tons of reading involved. Sure, many big games today like fortnite and cod require strategy and coordination, too, but they are very arcadey, adrenaline-pumping, or even addictive gambling affairs (like many mobile games). 

Have there been any studies about the effects of different types of games on children? Roblox vs. Dark Souls, etc? I want my kids to enjoy games growing up as I did, but I do see this ever numbing presence of thrill value and shortening of attention spans present if I give them free reign. Perhaps I'm idealizing the games I enjoyed and putting down my kids' preferences unfairly, but I do believe the kinds of games they play matter. Video games are one of the most popular forms of entertainment for kids, but they have such a short segment on here talking about it.

comment_text:
Cannabinoids CBD, THC, THCV, JWH-133 and dronabinol have been shown to outright slow, and in some cases block Alzheimer’s entirely. A key pathological marker of Alzheimer’s is the buildup of amyloid plaque in areas of the brain correlated with memory and cognition, commonly induced by the enzyme acetylcholinesterase (AChE). THC has been shown to inhibit this enzyme in numerous studies, and was described by The Scripps Research Institute as “a considerably superior inhibitor of [amyloid plaque] aggregation” than any currently approved drug for treating the disease, and a 2006 study by the University of Connecticut concluded that cannabinoid-based medications “will be the new breakout medicine treatments of the near future.” In collaboration, Complutense University and Cajal Institute discovered that in the brains of those deceased from Alzheimer’s compared with those of healthy people who died at a similar age, the endocannabinoid system in those with Alzheimer’s was drastically suppressed. Frequent re-stimulation of the endocannabinoid system with the phytocannabinoids found in cannabis seems to keep them active and actively fight the symptoms associated with Alzheimer’s. Phytocannabinoids bound to CB1 and CB2 receptors were also found to prevent microglial activation, halting the growth of Alzheimer’s and preventing the neurodegenerative process. A 2012 expert review concluded that stimulation of the endocannabinoid system is a prime target for Alzheimer’s therapy, with a request for more CBD studies. A 2007 study looking into CBD found it to have potent anti-neuroinflammatory properties, helping it to fight the symptoms associated with neurodegeneration, and a 2009 study by Israeli and Italian researchers found CBD to block the formation of amyloid plaques in a similar manner to THC.

An oft-forgotten negative side effect of Alzheimer’s is major loss of appetite, resulting in many victims becoming underweight and anorexic in severe cases. A study conducted by the International Psychogeriatric Association in 2003 treated 48 Alzheimer’s patients, an average age of 77 and all of which were diagnosed with anorexia, with cannabinoids. In all victims, weight gain was reported and recorded. Most patients also found themselves less agitated overall and saw functional improvements. video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text:
@22:42 I didn’t look up the study he published himself but I did check the other one he refers to. The study found a “SMALL TO MEDIUM EFFECT SIZE”. 

That statistical term (small to medium effect size) indicates that the observed differences in brain activation were noticeable but not large.

The study examined brain activation over 7 tasks. Out of 7 tasks, only 1 showed anything noticeable, “a small to medium effect size”. 

Heavy lifetime users were more likely to be male, to have lower income, and to have lower levels of education than nonusers. Heavy lifetime users also had higher scores for nicotine dependence severity and alcohol use relative to those with negative THC test results.

Even with all of that, there was no noticeable difference in 6 tasks, and only a small to medium noticeable difference in 1 task. 

Yet with all of the lower education, and nicotine use, and alcohol use, he wants to claim this study irrefutably shows that “marijuana is bad”. 

Btw, it was 1,003 participants. Not “1,021… 1,027” that he quotes. Clearly, his memory ain’t so great. Wonder what he’s been smokin’

Based on this weak study, I’m not wasting anymore time looking up the study he published. I doubt it’s any more conclusive than the JAMA one.

comment_text:
Lol. @22:42 I didn’t look up the study he published himself but I did check the other one he refers to. The study found a “SMALL TO MEDIUM EFFECT SIZE”. 

That statistical term (small to medium effect size) indicates that the observed differences in brain activation were noticeable but not large.

The study examined brain activation over 7 tasks. Out of 7 tasks, only 1 showed anything noticeable, “a small to medium effect size”. 

Heavy lifetime users were more likely to be male, to have lower income, and to have lower levels of education than nonusers. Heavy lifetime users also had higher scores for nicotine dependence severity and alcohol use relative to those with negative THC test results.

Even with all of that, there was no noticeable difference in 6 tasks, and only a small to medium noticeable difference in 1 task. 

Yet with all of the lower education, and nicotine use, and alcohol use, he wants to claim this study irrefutably shows that “marijuana is bad”. 

Btw, it was 1,003 participants. Not “1,021… 1,027” that he quotes. Clearly, his memory ain’t so great. Wonder what he’s been smokin’

Based on this weak study, I’m not wasting anymore time looking up the study he published. Have a feeling it’s just more Reefer Madness bologna 🤦‍♂️

comment_text:
@22:42 I didn’t look up the study he published himself but I did check the other one he refers to. The study found a “SMALL TO MEDIUM EFFECT SIZE”. 

That statistical term (small to medium effect size) indicates that the observed differences in brain activation were noticeable but not large.

The study examined brain activation over 7 tasks. Out of 7 tasks, only 1 showed anything noticeable, “a small to medium effect size”. 

Heavy lifetime users were more likely to be male, to have lower income, and to have lower levels of education than nonusers. Heavy lifetime users also had higher scores for nicotine dependence severity and alcohol use relative to those with negative THC test results.

Even with all of that, there was no noticeable difference in 6 tasks, and only a small to medium noticeable difference in 1 task. 

Yet with all of the lower education, and nicotine use, and alcohol use, he wants to claim this study irrefutably shows that “marijuana is bad”.

video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text:
@22:42 I didn’t look up the study he published himself but I did check the other one he refers to. The study found a “SMALL TO MEDIUM EFFECT SIZE”. 

That statistical term (small to medium effect size) indicates that the observed differences in brain activation were noticeable but not large.

The study examined brain activation over 7 tasks. Out of 7 tasks, only 1 showed anything noticeable, “a small to medium effect size”. 

Heavy lifetime users were more likely to be male, to have lower income, and to have lower levels of education than nonusers. Heavy lifetime users also had higher scores for nicotine dependence severity and alcohol use relative to those with negative THC test results.

Even with all of that, there was no noticeable difference in 6 tasks, and only a small to medium noticeable difference in 1 task. 

Yet with all of the lower education, and nicotine use, and alcohol use, he wants to claim this study irrefutably shows that “marijuana is bad”. 

Btw, it was 1,003 participants. Not “1,021… 1,027” that he quotes. Clearly, his memory ain’t so great. Wonder what he’s been smokin’

Based on this weak study, I’m not wasting anymore time looking up the study he published. Have a feeling it’s just more Reefer Madness bologna 🤦‍♂️

comment_text:
It’s okay for most adults. @22:42 I didn’t look up the study he published himself but I did check the other one he refers to. The study found a “SMALL TO MEDIUM EFFECT SIZE”. 

That statistical term (small to medium effect size) indicates that the observed differences in brain activation were noticeable but not large.

The study examined brain activation over 7 tasks. Out of 7 tasks, only 1 showed anything noticeable, “a small to medium effect size”. 

Heavy lifetime users were more likely to be male, to have lower income, and to have lower levels of education than nonusers. Heavy lifetime users also had higher scores for nicotine dependence severity and alcohol use relative to those with negative THC test results.

Even with all of that, there was no noticeable difference in 6 tasks, and only a small to medium noticeable difference in 1 task. 

Yet with all of the lower education, and nicotine use, and alcohol use, he wants to claim this study irrefutably shows that “marijuana is bad”. 

Btw, it was 1,003 participants. Not “1,021… 1,027” that he quotes. Clearly, his memory ain’t so great. Wonder what he’s been smokin’

Based on this weak study, I’m not wasting anymore time looking up the study he published. Have a feeling it’s just more Reefer Madness bologna 🤦‍♂️

comment_text:
@22:42 I didn’t look up the study he published himself but I did check the other one he refers to. The study found a “SMALL TO MEDIUM EFFECT SIZE”. 

That statistical term (small to medium effect size) indicates that the observed differences in brain activation were noticeable but not large.

The study examined brain activation over 7 tasks. Out of 7 tasks, only 1 showed anything noticeable, “a small to medium effect size”. 

Heavy lifetime users were more likely to be male, to have lower income, and to have lower levels of education than nonusers. Heavy lifetime users also had higher scores for nicotine dependence severity and alcohol use relative to those with negative THC test results.

Even with all of that, there was no noticeable difference in 6 tasks, and only a small to medium noticeable difference in 1 task. 

Yet with all of the lower education, and nicotine use, and alcohol use, he wants to claim this study irrefutably shows that “marijuana is bad”. 

Btw, it was 1,003 participants. Not “1,021… 1,027” that he quotes. Clearly, his memory ain’t so great. Wonder what he’s been smokin’

Based on this weak study, I’m not wasting anymore time looking up the study he published. Have a feeling it’s just more Reefer Madness bologna 🤦‍♂️

video_title: The No.1 Brain Doctor: This Parenting Mistake Ruins Your Kids Brain & Alcohol Will Ruin Yours!
comment_text:
Reducing caffeine, especially later in the day, can have a huge impact on sleep quality. Here’s why your experience makes perfect sense:
☕ Caffeine’s Half-Life & Sleep Disruption – Caffeine has a half-life of about 5-6 hours, meaning that even a noon coffee can still be affecting your nervous system well into the evening. Removing that midday dose likely helped reduce sleep fragmentation and nighttime awakenings.
🧠 Deep Sleep & Brain Detoxification – Caffeine blocks adenosine, the brain’s natural "sleep pressure" signal. By reducing caffeine intake, you’re allowing adenosine to build naturally, which promotes deeper, more restorative sleep—exactly what you’ve noticed!
🔄 Circadian Rhythm Reset – Eliminating that noon coffee likely helped synchronize your sleep-wake cycle. Caffeine can delay melatonin production, making it harder to fall asleep at night and leading to inconsistent sleep patterns.
❤ Physical & Mental Benefits – With better sleep, you’re probably experiencing improved mood, sharper focus, and more stable energy levels throughout the day. Sleep is also critical for cardiovascular health, immune function, and metabolic balance.

Here are some additional science-backed tips to optimize your sleep even further:
🌞 Get Morning Sunlight – Exposing yourself to natural morning light within the first hour of waking helps regulate your circadian rhythm, making it easier to fall asleep at night. Just 10–30 minutes of sunlight in the morning can enhance melatonin production later in the evening.
📵 Limit Screens Before Bed – Blue light from phones, TVs, and tablets suppresses melatonin, making it harder to fall asleep. Try switching to warm, dim lighting in the evening and reduce screen time at least 60–90 minutes before bed. If you must use screens, consider blue light-blocking glasses or night mode settings.
🛏 Optimize Your Sleep Environment - Keep your bedroom cool
🍽 Watch Your Evening Diet – Avoid heavy meals right before bed—digestion can interfere with deep sleep. Avoid alcohol, as it disrupts REM sleep and overall sleep architecture.
🧘‍♀ Develop a Wind-Down Routine – Reading, journaling, or light stretching can signal your body it’s time to relax. 
⏳ Keep a Consistent Sleep Schedule – Try to go to bed and wake up at the same time every day (even on weekends). This helps regulate your biological clock, making falling asleep and waking up easier.

I hope these tips were helpful to you!

comment_text:
@22:42 I didn’t look up the study he published himself but I did check the other one he refers to. The study found a “SMALL TO MEDIUM EFFECT SIZE”. 

That statistical term (small to medium effect size) indicates that the observed differences in brain activation were noticeable but not large.

The study examined brain activation over 7 tasks. Out of 7 tasks, only 1 showed anything noticeable, “a small to medium effect size”. 

Heavy lifetime users were more likely to be male, to have lower income, and to have lower levels of education than nonusers. Heavy lifetime users also had higher scores for nicotine dependence severity and alcohol use relative to those with negative THC test results.

Even with all of that, there was no noticeable difference in 6 tasks, and only a small to medium noticeable difference in 1 task. 

Yet with all of the lower education, and nicotine use, and alcohol use, he wants to claim this study irrefutably shows that “marijuana is bad”. 

Btw, it was 1,003 participants. Not “1,021… 1,027” that he quotes. Clearly, his memory ain’t so great. Wonder what he’s been smokin’

Based on this weak study, I’m not wasting anymore time looking up the study he published. Have a feeling it’s just more Reefer Madness bologna 🤦‍♂️

Humans’ justifications for discounting other animals’ suffering and denying their basic rights are based on speciesism and are strikingly similar to those that have been used to disregard women’s suffering and disallow them their fundamental rights.

Being violated without consent isn’t just a human problem. Animal agriculture is entirely reliant on female exploitation. On farms, female animals are confined, forcibly impregnated, and killed so their ovulation markers, milk, and other body parts can be sold for human consumption.

Cows are wonderful mothers who, just like humans, carry their babies for nine months and nurse them, developing a strong bond.

Cows make milk for the same reason women do: to feed their babies. They produce milk only when they’re pregnant or nursing. On dairy farms, they are repeatedly forcibly impregnated through artificial insemination while being restrained in a contraption the industry calls a “rape rack”. In commercial dairy farming, their babies are taken from them within 24 hours of birth, and if they are female, they will enter the same cycle of misery as their mother. The male calves are killed or sold into the veal industry.

Mother cows often bellow and call out frantically for their young for several days or weeks after they’ve been torn from them.

The strain of continual pregnancy exhausts cows and often leaves them emaciated, with mastitis (infected udders), or lame. When they are worn out and can no longer produce high volumes of milk, they are sent to the abattoir and killed.

Farmers treat hens like egg-laying machines. They use light and food to manipulate their reproductive systems to induce extra laying cycles, forcing them to produce as many as 300 eggs per year – far more than the 10 to 15 their ancestors produced in nature.

Because of this, they often suffer from cysts, infections, ovarian carcinomas, and reproductive tumours and sometimes multiple eggs become lodged inside them – which is life-threatening. Their bones often shatter from osteoporosis because their bodies are forced to produce unnaturally high quantities of eggshells, day after day, without rest.

When their egg production begins to wane, these sensitive animals are shoved into cramped crates and endure a harrowing journey to the abattoir. comment_text:
@22:42 I didn’t look up the study he published himself but I did check the other one he refers to. The study found a “SMALL TO MEDIUM EFFECT SIZE”. 

That statistical term (small to medium effect size) indicates that the observed differences in brain activation were noticeable but not large.

The study examined brain activation over 7 tasks. Out of 7 tasks, only 1 showed anything noticeable, “a small to medium effect size”. 

Heavy lifetime users were more likely to be male, to have lower income, and to have lower levels of education than nonusers. Heavy lifetime users also had higher scores for nicotine dependence severity and alcohol use relative to those with negative THC test results.

Even with all of that, there was no noticeable difference in 6 tasks, and only a small to medium noticeable difference in 1 task. 

Yet with all of the lower education, and nicotine use, and alcohol use, he wants to claim this study irrefutably shows that “marijuana is bad”. 

Btw, it was 1,003 participants. Not “1,021… 1,027” that he quotes. Clearly, his memory ain’t so great. Wonder what he’s been smokin’

Based on this weak study, I’m not wasting anymore time looking up the study he published. Have a feeling it’s just more Reefer Madness bologna 🤦‍♂️

comment_text:
@TheDiaryOfACEO

I have narcolepsy. I have, for my entire adult life, had a dysfunctional brain. The best way to describe having narcolepsy is that parts of your brain go to sleep when you don't want them to (during the day) and parts wake up when you don't want them to (during the night) and you functionally feel chronically severely sleep deprived. Your sleep cycles are disrupted and out of order, and your ability to stay awake and have normal cognitive functioning and retain memories, for example, is greatly affected. It's one of those diseases that completely disrupts and in my case ruins your life. I've been completely unable to get it under any real control more than a couple of years at a time, usually by being on high doses of stimulants, which causes its own set of problems. I have ADHD. Severely, because these symptoms overlap some daytime symptoms of narcolepsy. I am 41 and I feel like my brain is 200. I would love to know if Dr amen has any knowledge or information on what someone like me is supposed to do to have some semblance of a normal life. The worst part is, now, I have 2 young children who are being modeled a completely dysfunctional way of living because I'm physically incapable of modeling anything better. Their dad does the best he can to help out and to make up for the dysfunctional modeling they get from me, but I'm their mother. I really need help with this. Even sleep specialists of whom I've seen several over the years, just don't have any real answers for me. I've done CBT, taken several types and combinations of drugs, and made every effort I can to combat this. But, no pun intended, I'm just SO TIRED of living like this. There has to be something more.
